Turkish defense company **KayacÄ± Savunma** (KayacÄ± Defence) has signed an agreement with the **Turkish Coast Guard** and the **Presidency of Defense Industries** to begin official trials of the **OKHAN unmanned surface vehicle (USV)**. During the evaluation phase (6-9 months), additional operational requirements will be determined **to align the platform with the specific needs** of the Coast Guard.

The OKHAN USV is a 11.4-meter vessel equipped with a diesel-electric engine, allowing it to move at a maximum speed of **50 km/h for a range of 500 km**, and at a speed of **37 km/h for up to 740 km** (â—). The communication system's line-of-sight range is **27 km**, and via satellite channels **up to 200 km**. The USV can carry **up to 1 ton of payload** (â—) - weapon systems, radar cross-section reduction devices, radio frequency jammers, and various sensors. Additionally, the OKHAN is designed to be **compatible with UAVs and other small vessels**.

The integrated sensor suite includes a **navigation radar** with a range of 24 km, **electro-optical systems**, **satellite telemetry**, and **standard navigation equipment**.

The USV is **intended** for the following tasks:

â—¾Surveillance and reconnaissance;
â—¾Maritime security;
â—¾Search and rescue;
â—¾Border protection;
â—¾Environmental monitoring;
â—¾Combating illegal migration.

âœ¨Such vehicles, with their characteristics and cost, **can potentially replace patrol boats/ships** used for maritime border protection, **the maintenance of which and their crews costs millions annually**. Hundreds of multipurpose USVs, **costing the same as a single combat ship** that has become **an easy target at sea** with the emergence of UUVs and UAVs, can **secure all maritime operational zones from a safe distance**, preempting and localizing threats.

